00:43:40,884 --> 00:43:44,115
no fighting, except for fun,
no wanton littering.

476
00:43:44,188 --> 00:43:45,177
Oh!

477
00:43:45,322 --> 00:43:47,119
As far as possible, be polite.

478
00:43:47,191 --> 00:43:49,125
Now, screaming insanely,

479
00:43:49,193 --> 00:43:51,889
running round the house
making absurd and disgusting noises,

480
00:43:51,962 --> 00:43:56,092
throwing water bombs at the windows,
all of these are actively encouraged.

481
00:43:56,166 --> 00:43:59,602
Artie! In fact, really,
there's only one rule,

482
00:43:59,670 --> 00:44:01,865
and that is you've got to do as I tell you.

483
00:44:01,972 --> 00:44:04,440
It's just that I'm not going to tell you
to do very much.

484
00:44:04,508 --> 00:44:08,672
The aim is something we like to call
hog heaven.

485
00:44:08,746 --> 00:44:10,043
Okay.

486
00:44:11,148 --> 00:44:12,274
Shit!

487
00:44:14,151 --> 00:44:14,947
It's not funny.

488
00:44:20,924 --> 00:44:24,087
- Hey, are you okay?
- Yeah. It's just so hot.

489
00:44:24,428 --> 00:44:27,591
It's quite a shock, isn't it?
I remember when I first arrived,

490
00:44:27,665 --> 00:44:29,633
but it's a great place
when you get used to it.

491
00:44:29,733 --> 00:44:31,064
Yeah? Well...

492
00:44:33,170 --> 00:44:35,832
"It has more things that will kill you
than anywhere else.

493
00:44:35,906 --> 00:44:40,002
"Out of the world's 10 most poisonous
snakes, all are Australian."

494
00:44:41,045 --> 00:44:45,607
You'll be all right.
Hope you manage to sleep.

495
00:45:15,946 --> 00:45:17,106
No!

496
00:45:19,550 --> 00:45:20,812
No!

497
00:45:25,222 --> 00:45:26,689
No!

498
00:45:29,226 --> 00:45:32,286
- Do you submit? Do you submit?
- No! No!

499
00:45:36,633 --> 00:45:40,967
Geronimo!
I'm the king of the bed!

500
00:45:41,038 --> 00:45:44,633
- I'm the king of the bed!
- Tag team. You and Artie versus me.

501
00:45:44,708 --> 00:45:46,573
- Yeah! Yeah!
- No. I'll pass, thanks. That's fine...

502
00:45:46,643 --> 00:45:49,441
Hey, you don't get away that easy,
big boy!

503
00:45:49,513 --> 00:45:54,075
- Yeah!
- Don't! Dad, don't! Don't! Jesus!

504
00:46:14,671 --> 00:46:15,763
Nice one.

505
00:46:16,206 --> 00:46:18,970
Oh, my God. You've got to be kidding.

506
00:46:20,677 --> 00:46:22,076
Good, eh?

507
00:46:23,213 --> 00:46:25,204
- That is so high.
- I know.

508
00:46:25,516 --> 00:46:27,882
- But if the wire breaks...
- Don't worry about the wire.

509
00:46:27,985 --> 00:46:29,316
The wire's fine.

510
00:46:29,453 --> 00:46:31,580
I'm trying not to think
of that branch falling on him.

511
00:46:31,722 --> 00:46:35,681
- But, seriously, if he let go...
- That's why he's hanging on so tight.

512
00:46:36,827 --> 00:46:39,091
- Nice one.
- Be careful!

513
00:46:39,196 --> 00:46:41,994
I think you rather enjoy
upsetting mothers.

514
00:46:42,633 --> 00:46:44,225
What gives you that idea?

515
00:46:48,305 --> 00:46:50,432
- Only four weeks out of date.
- You've been eating them.

516
00:46:50,507 --> 00:46:52,498
Here, here. Take this.

517
00:46:55,078 --> 00:46:57,410
Sweetie, can you go
get the fairy bread?

518
00:46:57,481 --> 00:46:59,881
- Shall I put them here?
- Yes.

519
00:46:59,950 --> 00:47:02,510
- Hi. I'm Laura. Hi.
- I'm Barbara.

520
00:47:02,653 --> 00:47:05,520
- Arthur's grandmother.
- Oh! Pleased to meet you.

521
00:47:05,956 --> 00:47:08,686
- Is this one yours?
- Yes.

522
00:47:09,226 --> 00:47:12,354
- She's very pretty.
- Thank you.

523
00:47:13,664 --> 00:47:16,132
- Artie.
- Darling.

524
00:47:16,200 --> 00:47:19,033
- Hi, Nana.
- Happy birthday.

525
00:47:19,169 --> 00:47:20,864
Thank you, Nana.

526
00:47:23,340 --> 00:47:26,070
Hey. Glad you could come.

527
00:47:26,844 --> 00:47:28,812
He'll put someone's eye out with that.

528
00:47:28,879 --> 00:47:31,279
The thing is,
constant warnings are maddening

529
00:47:31,348 --> 00:47:34,112
for anyone aspiring to be an overlord.

530
00:47:34,985 --> 00:47:38,045
- I would have done this for you.
- It looks good, doesn't it?

531
00:47:38,155 --> 00:47:40,385
Well, if they eat this lot,
they'll be climbing the walls.

532
00:47:40,490 --> 00:47:42,253
- Tea?
- Yes, thank you.

533
00:47:53,704 --> 00:47:55,399
Where is Harry?

534
00:47:59,309 --> 00:48:01,174
Why has he come here now,
do you think?

535
00:48:01,245 --> 00:48:02,303
What do you mean?

536
00:48:02,412 --> 00:48:05,848
Perhaps your ex-wife thinks
you're back on the market.

537
00:48:05,916 --> 00:48:07,144
Thank you.

538
00:48:11,588 --> 00:48:14,557
I remember
Katy's seventh birthday party.

539
00:48:15,125 --> 00:48:18,026
We invited the whole class,
30 of them.

540
00:48:18,161 --> 00:48:21,130
They ran riot.
It was a complete disaster.

541
00:48:26,637 --> 00:48:30,971
I still see her, in the street or...

542
00:48:32,309 --> 00:48:35,107
And not like in a dream.

543
00:48:36,546 --> 00:48:40,141
- Actually there.
- Me, too.

544
00:48:48,992 --> 00:48:51,392
Everyone run around.
You've got to chase everyone, okay?

545
00:48:53,463 --> 00:48:55,624
- Three million!
- Three million?

546
00:48:55,732 --> 00:48:58,257
We'll be here for weeks.

547
00:48:58,368 --> 00:49:00,802
Get ready. I'm counting to 100.

548
00:49:00,871 --> 00:49:06,104
One, two, three, four, five...

549
00:49:25,128 --> 00:49:27,722
...99, 100!

550
00:49:28,732 --> 00:49:31,599
Coming, ready or not.

551
00:49:33,103 --> 00:49:36,197
Come on, little children.
Come to Daddy,

552
00:49:36,273 --> 00:49:39,071
because I love to play
with the little children

553
00:49:39,142 --> 00:49:41,633
and give them lots of lovely pressies.

554
00:49:41,712 --> 00:49:45,045
For God's sake. You're going
to get yourself bloody arrested.

555
00:49:45,115 --> 00:49:46,104
Aha!

556
00:49:46,583 --> 00:49:49,916
I think I see one of the little darlings.

557
00:49:53,123 --> 00:49:55,114
- Oh, I'm sorry. Sorry.
- No, no, no, no. It's okay.

558
00:49:55,225 --> 00:49:59,889
- You can't catch me. No, no.
- Come here, you horrible little goblin!

559
00:50:02,032 --> 00:50:05,468
Boys, boys, look what you made me do.

560
00:50:06,069 --> 00:50:10,096
You made me angry.
I didn't mean to shout at you.

561
00:50:12,843 --> 00:50:16,244
Come
and find me. Come and find me.

562
00:50:18,248 --> 00:50:20,273
I'm right here.

563
00:50:20,450 --> 00:50:22,884
I think I know that little voice.

564
00:50:23,720 --> 00:50:24,880
Gotcha!

565
00:50:31,995 --> 00:50:34,190
Happy birthday, birthday boy.

566
00:50:49,980 --> 00:50:51,743
"Just say yes"?

567
00:50:51,848 --> 00:50:54,681
It has the power to change
the way you live.

568
00:50:54,785 --> 00:50:57,253
- Really?
- It seems to work for us.

569
00:50:58,288 --> 00:51:02,782
- It's not just an easy way out?
- It's not easy at all. It's really difficult.

570
00:51:04,027 --> 00:51:08,020
Our kids ask us to do a whole range of
unsuitable things and we just go, "No."

571
00:51:08,131 --> 00:51:12,363
We don't even think about it.
That's the habit I'm trying to control.

572
00:51:12,436 --> 00:51:14,996
Artie says,
"Can we go and swim in the river?"

573
00:51:15,072 --> 00:51:17,905
I say, "No. I have to go
and buy some milk."

574
00:51:18,475 --> 00:51:20,705
And you don't worry
about spoiling him?

575
00:51:20,811 --> 00:51:23,211
No. It's what he needs.

576
00:51:23,280 --> 00:51:25,271
You're a brave man.

577
00:51:26,716 --> 00:51:29,150
- Thanks for everything.
- Bye.

578
00:52:14,264 --> 00:52:15,595
Yeah?

579
00:52:16,399 --> 00:52:18,663
What was that you were playing?

580
00:52:19,035 --> 00:52:20,662
Just something I made up.

581
00:52:20,770 --> 00:52:23,068
- It sounded good.
- Thanks.

582
00:52:27,744 --> 00:52:30,110
Do you and your mum
ever play together?

583
00:52:30,180 --> 00:52:31,670
Sometimes.

584
00:52:34,151 --> 00:52:36,676
I did love your mother very much,
you know.

585
00:52:40,157 --> 00:52:42,057
Then why did you leave?

586
00:52:45,662 --> 00:52:48,187
Married couples of my mother
and father's generation

587
00:52:48,265 --> 00:52:50,062
stayed together
for the sake of the children.

588
00:52:50,167 --> 00:52:52,397
We divorced for the same reason.

589
00:52:52,469 --> 00:52:54,960
Are you saying you divorced
for my sake?

590
00:52:56,506 --> 00:52:59,441
I thought it was because you got
another woman pregnant.

591
00:53:00,410 --> 00:53:02,401
Well, there was that, too.

592
00:53:06,082 --> 00:53:08,812
We had some dreadful fights,
you know.

593
00:53:11,988 --> 00:53:14,889
I was no match for your mother
in combat.

594
00:53:18,195 --> 00:53:23,030
It can't have been all bad. You had me.

595
00:53:23,133 --> 00:53:26,159
No, of course not.
In the beginning, it was great.

596
00:53:29,873 --> 00:53:33,001
Listen, there's something
I want to ask you.

597
00:53:33,076 --> 00:53:34,509
Look, if you're imagining that

598
00:53:34,611 --> 00:53:37,136
your mother and I would
ever get back together again...

599
00:53:37,247 --> 00:53:38,714
Jesus, Dad.

600
00:53:39,916 --> 00:53:43,044
Her boyfriend's just moved in,
for Christ's sake.

601
00:53:43,153 --> 00:53:46,384
- Really? When?
- I don't know. A few months ago.

602
00:53:47,724 --> 00:53:51,592
- How's that for you?
- I'm away at school mostly.

603
00:53:54,364 --> 00:53:56,025
What's he like?

604
00:53:58,034 --> 00:53:59,399
He's nice.

605
00:54:03,039 --> 00:54:07,169
Anyway, I just wanted to say thanks
for all your help today.

606
00:54:08,812 --> 00:54:10,211
You were great.

607
00:54:47,317 --> 00:54:51,185
It's a huge goal. It's a wonder-strike.
It's a wonder-strike.

608
00:54:51,321 --> 00:54:55,280
- Don't want to play soccer.
- Why not?

609
00:54:56,192 --> 00:55:01,494
<i>Funny thing, isn't it? The minute
you think you're getting things sorted</i>

610
00:55:01,765 --> 00:55:04,563
<i>is the moment it all starts to fall apart.</i>

611
00:55:13,677 --> 00:55:16,168
- There it is!
- The ball went the other way!

612
00:55:17,147 --> 00:55:19,047
For God's sake.

613
00:55:21,451 --> 00:55:26,479
Guys, guys, can you put your
dirty clothes in the laundry baskets?

614
00:55:26,589 --> 00:55:29,319
Jeez! Do I have to do everything
around here?

615
00:55:29,392 --> 00:55:32,725
- Daddy, can I have some Coke?
- "Can I have some Coke," what?

616
00:55:32,796 --> 00:55:34,320
Can I have some Coke now?

617
00:55:34,397 --> 00:55:35,955
Can I teach you some manners, Arthur?

618
00:55:36,032 --> 00:55:39,866
- N-O. Mind your own business.
- "Just say yes."

619
00:55:39,969 --> 00:55:41,527
Put some bloody clothes on,
both of you.

620
00:55:41,604 --> 00:55:43,435
- Why?
- You know why.

621
00:55:43,506 --> 00:55:45,872
- Laura's bringing Lucy round.
- Why are you so angry?

622
00:55:45,942 --> 00:55:48,877
I'm not angry.
What makes you think I'm angry?

623
00:55:49,813 --> 00:55:52,247
- Hey, welcome.
- Hi.

624
00:55:52,315 --> 00:55:54,283
Hey, guess what.
One of our chooks had ducklings.

625
00:55:54,384 --> 00:55:56,079
- What?
- Chickens that can swim.

626
00:55:56,080 --> 00:55:58,351
- And fly.
- And shit on your head.

627
00:55:59,122 --> 00:56:01,955
- Can I come and see them?
- Of course you can.

628
00:56:02,025 --> 00:56:05,517
- Drink? One glass? Family red.
- I've got some things to do.

629
00:56:05,628 --> 00:56:07,118
- I should get back.
- One glass.

630
00:56:09,799 --> 00:56:11,790
- Leave those.
- Are you sure?

631
00:56:11,868 --> 00:56:16,202
Absolutely. I've discovered
this amazing cupboard in the kitchen,

632
00:56:16,272 --> 00:56:19,469
which not only stores the dishes,
it actually cleans them.

633
00:56:19,542 --> 00:56:20,804
Really?

634
00:56:22,011 --> 00:56:25,310
The housework has come
as a big shock, I have to admit,

635
00:56:25,382 --> 00:56:28,681
even though I watched so much of it
over the years.

636
00:56:28,785 --> 00:56:31,982
The cooking, the cleaning,
the ironing, the shopping,

637
00:56:32,122 --> 00:56:33,749
hoovering the carpets
when they change color...

638
00:56:33,823 --> 00:56:35,688
How did you meet Katy?

639
00:56:37,127 --> 00:56:38,924
I interviewed her.

640
00:56:40,430 --> 00:56:42,227
She was an equestrian.

641
00:56:45,435 --> 00:56:48,199
I met her at some horse trials
in England.

642
00:56:48,805 --> 00:56:50,898
She was with the Aussie team.

643
00:56:51,007 --> 00:56:54,875
I made her pregnant,
she came back to be near her parents.

644
00:56:55,512 --> 00:56:57,002
I followed.

645
00:56:58,281 --> 00:57:00,078
What was she like?

646
00:57:00,583 --> 00:57:04,144
Uniquely endowed
with intelligence, rowdiness,

647
00:57:05,321 --> 00:57:08,256
sex appeal, energy,

648
00:57:12,262 --> 00:57:14,526
and, as it turned out, cancer.

649
00:57:35,351 --> 00:57:39,549
And then one day Lucy asked me,
"Mummy, what is dope?"

650
00:57:40,023 --> 00:57:41,957
- And what did you say?
- I said,

651
00:57:42,025 --> 00:57:44,186
"Dope is a special name
I like to call Daddy."

652
00:57:44,260 --> 00:57:46,285
- What is his name?
- It's Bree.

653
00:57:46,362 --> 00:57:48,922
Brie? Like the runny cheese?

654
00:57:48,998 --> 00:57:53,162
I haven't heard that one before.
I've got to drive.

655
00:57:56,005 --> 00:57:58,166
So, how are things since the divorce?

656
00:57:58,241 --> 00:58:00,971
Fine. He was a terrible husband

657
00:58:01,044 --> 00:58:03,945
but okay dad,
you know, now that he's clean.

658
00:58:06,549 --> 00:58:08,517
So, what is it you want?

659
00:58:09,853 --> 00:58:11,718
Something I can't have.

660
00:58:14,991 --> 00:58:18,825
I mean, I've got plenty of people
I can do things with.

661
00:58:18,928 --> 00:58:21,726
I've just got no one
I can do nothing with.

662
00:58:28,238 --> 00:58:29,432
Hi.

663
00:58:37,680 --> 00:58:39,739
We'd better be going, I think.

664
00:58:46,422 --> 00:58:50,324
- I never want to see Lucy ever again.
- What?

665
00:58:50,426 --> 00:58:51,723
She spoils every game,

666
00:58:51,794 --> 00:58:54,888
and she's always supposed to be
the big sister and boss me around.

667
00:58:54,964 --> 00:58:56,226
I thought you wanted to go
and live with them?

668
00:58:56,332 --> 00:58:58,129
I don't anymore.

669
00:58:58,130 --> 00:59:00,868
Well, Laura's my friend. I'm not going
to stop seeing her on your account.

670
00:59:00,970 --> 00:59:02,733
We'll see about that.

671
00:59:04,874 --> 00:59:08,071
He's not upset because of Lucy.
It's because of you.

672
00:59:08,745 --> 00:59:11,942
He had you all to himself,
and then I came along,

673
00:59:12,282 --> 00:59:14,512
...and now Laura.
- Laura?

674
00:59:15,251 --> 00:59:18,118
She's a friend. Can I not have friends?

675
00:59:18,888 --> 00:59:21,550
God, Dad, anyone can see
how much you fancy her.

676
00:59:26,129 --> 00:59:28,188
Don't be so bloody precocious.

677
00:59:57,860 --> 00:59:59,623
- You wanted a word?
- Yeah.

678
00:59:59,729 --> 01:00:02,562
I see you've assigned coverage
of the Open to Digby.

679
01:00:02,632 --> 01:00:04,395
Yeah, yeah,
I just thought he could bring...

680
01:00:04,467 --> 01:00:06,025
I want you there.

681
01:00:06,836 --> 01:00:08,326
I've done it for the last four years.
I just thought...

682
01:00:08,404 --> 01:00:11,669
Look, I cut you a lot of slack
when Katy was ill,

683
01:00:11,741 --> 01:00:13,902
you know,
and then after she passed away.

684
01:00:14,010 --> 01:00:17,002
- Three months, Joe.
- I know, and I appreciate it.

685
01:00:21,084 --> 01:00:23,746
Artie. Hey, cut that out.

686
01:00:24,821 --> 01:00:27,153
Sorry, he's a bit under the weather.

687
01:00:27,290 --> 01:00:29,724
I want you there, Joe,
from the first point to the last.

688
01:00:29,792 --> 01:00:32,283
I need my top sports writer covering
top sporting events.

689
01:00:32,362 --> 01:00:35,195
Otherwise, you're not
my top sports writer, eh?

690
01:00:39,102 --> 01:00:40,228
Come on.

691
01:01:16,706 --> 01:01:17,866
I have checked all the airlines.

692
01:01:17,940 --> 01:01:21,171
There's absolutely no seats
available for the boys.

693
01:01:21,244 --> 01:01:23,940
Well, maybe I could drive.
What is it, seven hours?

694
01:01:24,047 --> 01:01:26,345
Ditto hotels. Everything's booked.

695
01:01:34,090 --> 01:01:38,356
So, those are done.
Now, what about this one?

696
01:01:42,265 --> 01:01:44,324
- Yeah, sure.
- That one there.

697
01:01:47,403 --> 01:01:48,802
Excuse me.

698
01:01:50,840 --> 01:01:53,900
- Is everything okay?
- Yeah, how are you?

699
01:01:55,011 --> 01:01:57,275
Busy. We've got the winemakers here.

700
01:01:58,047 --> 01:02:00,106
Listen, I'm in a bit of a jam.

701
01:02:00,583 --> 01:02:03,108
I was wondering if you might be able
to stay down at the house

702
01:02:03,109 --> 01:02:05,078
...with Harry and Artie.
- Hmm. When?

703
01:02:05,955 --> 01:02:08,446
Next week. I have to go away
to cover the tennis.

704
01:02:08,558 --> 01:02:10,082
- This coming week?
- Yeah.

705
01:02:10,159 --> 01:02:12,024
Shouldn't you have
thought of this before?

706
01:02:13,863 --> 01:02:16,195
Well, I've been trying to take them
with me, but it's not possible.

707
01:02:16,265 --> 01:02:18,028
Why don't you ask that girl
you're seeing?

708
01:02:18,101 --> 01:02:20,262
- What girl?
- The one at Arthur's party.

709
01:02:20,369 --> 01:02:22,337
She looked perfectly at home to me.

710
01:02:22,405 --> 01:02:25,704
One minute, Flick wants me back.
The next, I'm seeing someone.

711
01:02:25,808 --> 01:02:28,572
- Well, aren't you?
- No, I'm not.

712
01:02:28,644 --> 01:02:32,842
Look, we're really stretched here, Joe.
I can't go anywhere right now.

713
01:02:32,915 --> 01:02:35,748
Well, is there any chance
they could come here to you?

714
01:02:35,885 --> 01:02:37,648
